A
STUDY
OF
WHISTLING
ATMOSPHERICS
PART
DIFFUSENESS
DIFFUSENESS
DEFINED
AS
THE
AVERAGE
TIME
DURATION
OF
WHISTLER
ENERGY
ON
A
FIXED
FREQUENCY
IS
FOUND
TO
BE
TWICE
AS
LARGE
FOR
LONG
AS
FOR
SHORT
WHISTLERS
TO
BE
INDEPENDENT
OF
SEASON
AND
TIME
OF
DAY
AND
TO
BE
LINEARLY
RELATED
TO
GEOMAGNETIC
LATITUDE
AND
WHISTLER
DISPERSION
